AWS global infrastructure:

•	AWS Global Footprint: AWS operates numerous geographic regions worldwide, each containing multiple availability zones (AZs), which are clusters of data centers.
•	Availability Zones: Each AZ consists of one or more data centers with independent power, networking, and connectivity, typically within 60 miles of each other, enabling high availability and fault tolerance.
•	Regions: A region is made up of multiple AZs, usually within the same country to meet data sovereignty requirements. Deploying applications across multiple AZs in a region enhances fault tolerance.
•	Edge Networks: AWS uses edge locations and regional edge caches to deliver content closer to users with low latency, forming a content delivery network (CDN) that caches data nearer to end users for faster access.

This infrastructure design supports building highly available, fault-tolerant, and scalable applications, which is essential knowledge for designing AWS solutions effectively.

AWS shared responsibility model and cloud security:
•	Shared Responsibility Model: AWS is responsible for the security "of" the cloud (physical infrastructure, host OS, virtualization layer, data centers), while customers are responsible for security "in" the cloud (guest OS, data encryption, IAM, network security).
•	Customer Responsibilities: Include patching guest operating systems on EC2 instances, managing IAM user access and secret keys, configuring virtual firewalls and security groups, and implementing data encryption.
•	AWS Responsibilities: Include maintaining physical servers, host OS, hypervisor, and underlying infrastructure for abstracted services like AWS Lambda, S3, and DynamoDB.
•	Service Types: Infrastructure-as-a-service (e.g., EC2) requires more customer management; abstracted services (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) provide built-in infrastructure security but customers still manage data encryption and access policies.

Understanding this model is crucial for designing secure, compliant AWS architectures and aligns well with your interest in cloud computing and security.

AWS Well-Architected Framework module:

•	The AWS Well-Architected Framework guides designing secure, high-performing, resilient, and efficient cloud architectures.
•	It is organized into pillars, each focusing on critical aspects like security, reliability, performance, cost optimization, and sustainability.
•	The framework provides design patterns (best practices) and anti-patterns (common pitfalls) for each pillar.
•	Answering foundational questions from the framework helps identify vulnerabilities and areas for improvement in your cloud infrastructure.
•	Applying the framework helps ensure compliance with security and regulatory requirements, optimize costs, and improve overall system reliability.
•	It supports making informed trade-offs between cost, performance, and reliability depending on the environment (e.g., test vs. production).

This framework is essential for building robust AWS solutions aligned with industry best practices.

AWS Well-Architected Framework pillars covered in this module:
•	Operational Excellence: Focuses on running and improving cloud operations to deliver business value. Key principles include treating operations as code, making small reversible changes, anticipating failure, and learning from incidents.
•	Security: Ensures protection of data, systems, and assets. Design principles include strong identity foundation, traceability, layered security, automation, data protection in transit and at rest, and preparing for security events.
•	Reliability: Ensures systems work correctly and recover from failures. Principles include automatic recovery, testing recovery procedures, horizontal scaling, capacity management, and change automation.
•	Performance Efficiency: Uses resources efficiently to meet system requirements. Encourages adopting advanced technologies like serverless, global deployment, experimentation, and considering hardware/software efficiency.
•	Cost Optimization: Focuses on delivering business value at the lowest cost. Principles include cloud financial management, consumption-based pricing, measuring efficiency, avoiding unnecessary spending, and continuous cost optimization.
•	Sustainability: Addresses environmental and societal impact. Encourages understanding impact, setting sustainability goals, maximizing resource utilization, adopting efficient hardware/software, using managed services, and reducing downstream effects.


These pillars guide designing secure, reliable, efficient, cost-effective, and sustainable AWS cloud architectures aligned with best practices.

